      <hedline>
        <hl1>What to Look For as Bush and Gore Debate; Mikes and Lecterns</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Amanda Lewis letter on negotiations between Bush and Gore camps over conditions of Presidential debates</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Debate Stakes Seen as Critical by Candidates'' (front page, Oct. 1):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Debate Stakes Seen as Critical by Candidates'' (front page, Oct. 1):</p>
        <p>Your article about the negotiating between the Bush and Gore camps over microphones, the height of the lecterns and the timing of questions made me wonder: if each voter could get these two in a room minus the makeup, costumes, campaign teams and sound bites, would either George W. Bush or Al Gore prove worthy of election to office?</p>
        <p>AMANDA LEWIS  Des Moines, Oct. 1, 2000</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
